&gt;          From dms@hermes.ai.mit.edu Wed Apr 29 09:29:55 1987
&gt;       
&gt;          Why not have names like 'berkeley.UCal.edu', and 'Irvine.UCal.edu'?
&gt;
&gt;  Riddle me this, BatMan ... why is the tag "EDU" still there?
&gt; 
&gt;  /jordan

I'm certainly new to the networks, and perhaps very clueless on this subject,
but it should be noted that an amazing number of people who aren't
"computer people" are using the nets, and more are coming every day.  
As they become familiar with the system, they start wandering around the
network learning more and more.

The point is: If adding ".EDU" tells me that "Irvine.UCal.Edu" is probably
the University of California at Irvine and NOT the offices of the
Union Oil Company of California, (some of which happen to be in Irvine),
then I am all in favor of typing those four characters.

Eventually, network addresses are going to have to deal with most government,
commercial, educational and major private organizations in the world. Why
not start dividing them up in a reasonably way now, instead of waiting?

